{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"cbcf97b7-6411-4fb5-bfe2-8ade9c73c9f1","content":"Yes, both are known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Here's what's happening:\n\n---\n\n## 1. Lost test history in Azure DevOps\n\nMSTest v4 changed the **default test-ID generation strategy**. IDs are now based on a fully-qualified format, so Azure DevOps treats every test as new.\n\n**Fix** — add to your `.runsettings`:\n\n```xml\n<MSTest>\n  <TestIdGenerationStrategy>Legacy</TestIdGenerationStrategy>\n</MSTest>\n```\n\nOr keep the new IDs and accept a one-time history reset.\n\n---\n\n## 2. `TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`\n\nIn v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a **class-level context** — it has no associated test method. Accessing `TestName` now throws `InvalidOperationException`. In v3 it accidentally returned the first test's name, which was unreliable.\n\n**Fix** for your code — don't use `TestName` in class init:\n\n```csharp\n[ClassInitialize]\npublic static void ClassInit(TestContext context)\n{\n    // context.TestName is not available here in v4\n    // Use context.FullyQualifiedTestClassName instead, or\n    // move per-test logic to [TestInitialize]\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n## Other v4 breaking changes to watch for\n\n| Area | Change |\n|------|--------|\n| **Parallel execution** | Enabled by default. Add `[assembly: Parallelize(Scope = ExecutionScope.ClassLevel)]` or disable explicitly if tests aren't thread-safe. |\n| **`[DataRow]` type matching** | Stricter — implicit numeric conversions (e.g., `int` → `long`) no longer work; values must match parameter types exactly. |\n| **Constructor injection** | `TestContext` can now be injected via constructor. Property setter injection still works but constructor takes priority. |\n| **`TestContext.Properties`** | Read-only in class/assembly-level contexts. |\n| **Timeout behavior** | `[Timeout]` now uses `CancellationToken` cooperative cancellation by default instead of thread-abort. Long-running code must observe cancellation. |\n\n---\n\nWould you like me to update your `SetupTests.cs` to be v4-compatible?","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cddc4695-b62b-442c-8f9f-30decc991fd4","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about known MSTest v4 breaking changes. Let me address both issues they're seeing:\n\n1. **Tests appearing as brand new in Azure DevOps (no history)**: In MSTest v4, the default test ID generation changed. MSTest v3 used a legacy test ID format, while v4 uses a new fully-qualified ID format. This means Azure DevOps sees them as completely different tests, losing the historical association. The fix is to set `<TestIdGenerationStrategy>` to `Legacy` in a `.runsettings` file or project property.\n\n2. **`TestContext.TestName` in `[ClassInitialize]`**: In MSTest v4, the `TestContext` passed to `[ClassInitialize]` is a class-level context, not tied to any specific test method. Accessing `TestName` on it now throws an `InvalidOperationException` because there's no \"current test\" at class initialization time. \n\nIn v3, this would unreliably return whichever test happened to run first and trigger the initialization. Beyond these two issues, there are several other notable changes worth mentioning: `DataRow` now enforces strict type matching without implicit conversions, test class constructors can now receive `TestContext` directly, `DeploymentItem` behavior has shifted, and parallel execution is enabled by default. There are also changes to `AssemblyInitialize`/`AssemblyCleanup` and `TestContext.Properties` is now read-only in certain scenarios.","outputTokens":925,"requestId":"BC43:1129F2:2303CD0:26E0AE8:69FAAAFC"},"id":"d29adeed-c98f-476b-ae96-25dfce2dba1d","timestamp":"2026-05-06T02:44:31.780Z","parentId":"27afb8c2-975c-477e-a0a5-97a7d93f2d5c"}
